  "doi": "10.1074/jbc.m117.810382",
  "title": "Structural basis for clonal diversity of the human T-cell response to a dominant influenza virus epitope.",
  "journal": "The Journal of biological chemistry",
  "year": 2017,
  "authors": "Yang X, Chen G, Weng NP, Mariuzza RA."
 },
 "executive_summary": "HLA-A2-restricted CD8+ T cells recognize the immunodominant influenza A virus epitope GILGFVFTL (GIL) through TCRs that fall into two classes: canonical TCRs using TRAV27/TRBV19 (\u223c60% of the response) and non-canonical TCRs with diverse gene usage (\u223c40%). This study determined the 1.7 \u00c5 crystal structure of a non-canonical TCR (F50, TRAV13-1/TRBV27) bound to GIL-HLA-A2 and compared it to a canonical TCR (JM22) previously crystallized on the same ligand, revealing that F50 and JM22 adopt markedly different binding orientations\u2014crossing angles of 29\u00b0 versus 69\u00b0, different focal points along the MHC \u03b11 helix, and distinct residues (tryptophan versus arginine) engaging the GIL-HLA-A2 interface. This structural diversity explains how a single, featureless peptide epitope can be recognized through multiple independent molecular solutions, enabling a polyclonal TCR repertoire that protects against viral escape mutations and maintains protection even if individual TCR clones are lost. The findings underscore how clonal diversity in anti-viral immunity derives not from a single optimal TCR-pMHC interaction but from multiple structurally distinct yet functionally competent solutions to the same recognition problem.",
